    type='think',
    think="Now I have all the information I need. Let me compile my findings and
write the review report.\n\nKey issues to report:\n\n**Blocking:**\n- None that 
I consider truly blocking. The overlay depth issue is significant but existed be
fore and doesn't break core functionality in typical cases.\n\n**Major:**\n1. `U
IDialog` message text color uses `UITheme.lightInk` (#666666) instead of the `#c
ccccc` specified in the design spec. This makes the message text much darker and
potentially less readable.\n2. `UIPanel` overlay added as container child has in
correct depth semantics. The overlay `setDepth(UIDepthLayer.Overlay)` is ineffec
tive because it's inside a Container. In Phaser 3, children inside containers do
n't have their depth values respected globally. The overlay is rendered at the c
ontainer's depth. This breaks the depth hierarchy guarantee - non-modal panels a
t depth 3001+ could render above a modal dialog at 3000.\n3. Designs/issue-19 te
st file `UIAlert.test.ts` expects `UITheme.goldBrown` for warning type, but shou
ld expect `UITheme.warning`. This indicates the design deliverables weren't full
y synchronized with the app fixes.\n4. `UIButton.setTexture()` calls `setupInter
action()` without first cleaning up old listeners from the container itself. Wai
t, listeners are on `this.background`, which is destroyed. But `setupInteraction
()` does `target.setInteractive({ useHandCursor: true })`. Actually, I need to r
econsider. When `this.background.destroy()` is called, Phaser destroys the GameO
bject. But the event listeners on the old background are stored on the old backg
round object. Since it's destroyed, they're gone. The new background gets new li
steners. So this is fine. I'll skip this one.\n\nActually, let me reconsider iss
ue #2 (overlay depth). Is it really Major? Let me think:\n- In Phaser 3, when yo
u add a GameObject to a Container, it is removed from the scene's display list\n
- The container renders its children in the order they were added\n- The `depth`
property of children is ignored by the container's rendering\n- The container's 
`depth` is what matters for global sorting\n\nSo the overlay inside UIPanel is r
endered at the panel's depth (e.g., 3000 for dialogs), not at 4000. This means:\
n1. A non-modal Panel at depth 3001 would render ABOVE a Dialog at 3000 and its 
overlay\n2. The overlay doesn't actually block interaction with things at depth 
3001+\n\nHowever, looking at `this.overlay.setInteractive()`, the overlay DOES b
lock pointer events within its bounds (which is the entire screen). So even if s
omething renders visually on top, the overlay might still capture clicks. But in
Phaser 3, input handling also uses depth ordering - objects with higher depth re
ceive input first. So a Panel at 3001 would receive input before the Dialog's ov
erlay at 3000. This means you could click on the Panel at 3001 even though a mod
al Dialog is open.\n\nThis is definitely a bug, but it's pre-existing. I'll mark
it as Major.\n\nWait, I should double check Phaser 3 input depth behavior. In Ph
aser 3, input is handled based on the display list order. For objects in the sce
ne, higher depth = tested first. But for objects inside containers... containers
handle their own input. The container's input manager tests children in reverse 
order (last added = first tested). So the overlay (added first) is tested LAST. 
This means the background (added second) is tested before the overlay. But both 
are interactive. If you click on the panel background, it would be captured by t
he background, not the overlay.\n\nBut wait - `this.overlay.setInteractive()` is
called, but the overlay is a Rectangle. When inside a container, the container's
`input` system handles hit testing for children. The overlay covers the entire p
anel area (since it's `camera.width * 2` but clipped by the container? No, it's 
not clipped). Actually, the overlay is huge, so clicking anywhere would hit it. 
But the background is also interactive? In UIPanel, `createBackground()` does NO
T call `setInteractive()` on the background. So only the overlay is interactive 
in UIPanel.\n\nIn UIDialog, `createButtons()` creates UIButtons which are intera
ctive. The overlay is also interactive. But the messageText is not. So clicks on
the message pass through to the overlay.\n\nThe issue is more about visual rende
ring than input blocking. The overlay at depth 3000 won't visually block a Panel
at depth 3001. But the Panel at 3001 might still not be clickable if the overlay
captures the input... Actually no, the Panel at 3001 is at a higher depth, so it
's tested first for input.\n\nOK, I think this is genuinely a Major issue, but i
t's complex to explain and existed before. I'll include it.\n\nLet me also check
if there are any other issues I missed.\n\nOne more thing: In `UIDialog.ts`, the
`panelConfig` passed to `super()` includes `onOverlayClick: undefined`. Then aft
er `super()`, if `closeOnOverlay` is true, it does:\n```typescript\nthis.overlay
.removeAllListeners('pointerdown');\nthis.overlay.on('pointerdown', () => this.c
ancel());\n```\n\nBut `removeAllListeners('pointerdown')` removes ALL pointerdow
n listeners. If UIPanel had added other listeners (which it doesn't), they'd be 
removed too. More importantly, it also removes any listeners that might have bee
n added by other code before the dialog was created. But since the overlay is cr
eated inside UIPanel's constructor, and no other code has access to it yet, this
is fine.\n\nHowever, if `closeOnOverlay` is false, the overlay still has the UIP
anel's `onOverlayClick` listener (which is an empty function). This means the ov
erlay is interactive and captures clicks, but does nothing. This is fine - it bl
ocks clicks from passing through to the scene.\n\nActually wait, looking at UIPa
nel's `createOverlay()`:\n```typescript\nthis.overlay.on('pointerdown', () => {\
n  this.config.onOverlayClick?.();\n});\n```\n\nSo if `onOverlayClick` is undefi
ned (as passed from UIDialog), this becomes `() => { undefined?.() }` which is `
() => {}`. The overlay still captures the click. This is correct for modal behav
ior.\n\nOne more issue: In `UIDialog`, `panelConfig.onClose: config.onClose` is 
passed. But `config.onClose` is inherited from `UIPanelConfig`. However, `UIDial
og` doesn't have a close button (`showClose: false`), so `onClose` is never trig
gered. This is dead code but harmless.\n\nNow let me also check `UIAlert.show()`
and `hide()` for timer cleanup. In `show()`:\n```typescript\nif (this.autoHideEv
ent) {\n  this.autoHideEvent.remove();\n  this.autoHideEvent = undefined;\n}\n``
`\nThis prevents duplicate timers if show() is called twice. Good.\n\nIn `hide()
`:\n```typescript\nif (this.autoHideEvent) {\n  this.autoHideEvent.remove();\n  
this.autoHideEvent = undefined;\n}\n```\nGood cleanup.\n\nSame pattern in UIToas
t.show() and dismiss(). Good.\n\nLet me now think about the `designs/issue-19/` 
vs `apps/phaser3/src/ui/` drift more carefully. The PR includes both directories
. The `designs/` directory is supposed to be the design deliverable per `agent-d
esign-guide.md`:\n> 所有 UI 代码写入 designs/issue-{{ .Vars.issueNumber }}/src/
，目录结构与 apps/phaser3/src/ 对齐\n\nBut then the actual changes are applied t
o `apps/phaser3/src/ui/`. The drift between them means the design directory is n
